bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: Medical Center Public Relations at The George Washington University became the Medical Center Office of Communications and Marketing, circa 1999. It was previously known as the Department of Marketing and Public Relations (c.1994-99) and before that the Office of Public Relations. It publishes "Progress" (1989-Present), which evolved from the "Friday Report" (1970-89), and "GW Health and Medicine magazine" (1965-Present). The Director of Medical Center Public Relations reports to the Director of the Medical Center. The office also maintains publicity files on staff and faculty.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include biographical files, photographs, slides, videotapes, press kits, publications, books, and artifacts. They range in date from 1960-91, and were transferred to the University Archives by the Director of Medical Center Public Relations. Note: Not all series are processed. Ask staff for assistance.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into fourteen series: five relate to faculty and five are visual materials. The remaining four are as listed: Medical Center history, Articles, Graduating class, and Departmental files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs. The material dates from 1975-83. The subjects of these images are faculty, staff, and events. scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains pamphlets, manuals, publications, correspondence, convocations, student handbook, alumni council, meeting minutes, by-laws, constitution, photographs, slides, plaques, and books. This material dates form 1947-99. Subjects of this materials include Governing Board, Medical Society, Medical Alumni Association, alumni reunion weekends, commencements, oration by Fred Gibbs, Ross Hall and buildings on H Street, the Health Sciences chartering ceremony, the statue of George Washington on Washington Circle, Women's Board.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series includes photographs (slides, negatives, proofs and prints) received from the School of Medicine and Health Sciences communications and marketing unit. The subjects include mostly faculty and staff, but also some events such as conferences, and appear to date mostly from the late 1990s into the very early 2000s. Some of the images are partially organized and identified, but many are loose and unidentified
